rk |accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref> is a [[Cree]] linguist who has worked on teaching and documenting the [[Plains Cree|Plains Cree language]].\n\n\n== Career ==\n\nIn 1982, Okim\u0101sis started work on [[Plains Cree|Cree language]] programs at the [[Saskatchewan]] Indian Federated college (now the [[First Nations University of Canada]]). She published a textbook, workbook, and teaching grammar of the Cree language called ''Cree, Language of the Plains''.<ref name=\"CLN:bio\" />\n\nOkim\u0101sis has been instrumental in developing and promoting the use of the standard [[Latin script|Roman orthography]] for writing the Cree language.<ref name=\"CL:park\">{{cite web |last1=Ogg |first1=Arden |title=Regina opens Jean Okim\u00e2sis Park |url=https://creeliteracy.org/2019/03/31/regina-opens-jean-okimasis-park/ |website=Cree Literacy Network |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> In 2008, she cowrote ''How to Spell it in Cree (The Standard Roman Orthography)'' with [[Arok Wolvengrey]].\n\n\n== Recognition ==\n\nOkim\u0101sis received the [[YWCA]] Woman of Distinction Award in 2000, and an honourary doctorate from the [[University of Regina]] in 2005.<ref name=\"CBC:Park\">{{cite news |title=Regina planning commission wants to name a park after Jean Okimasis |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/jean-okimasis-regina-city-park-1.4771085 |accessdate=6 March 2020 |agency=CBC News |date=August 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, a park was named after Okim\u0101sis in [[Regina]].<ref name=\"CBC:Park\"/><ref name=\"CL:park\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Arok Wolvengrey]]\n*[[Solomon Ratt]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book\n |last      = Okim\u0101sis\n |first     = Jean\n |title     = Cree: Language of the Plains/n\u0113hiyaw\u0113win: paskw\u0101wi-p\u012bkiskw\u0113win\n |publisher = Canadian Plains Research Center\n |editor    = \n |url       = \n |year      = 2004\n |place     = Regina\n |isbn      = 0-88977-155-3\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |last1 